Part 5

The boardroom emptied out slowly, the way rooms do when everyone in them is pretending not to be in a hurry. 

Vikram stood at the wide glass window after the last mahogany chair had scraped back against the carpet. He kept his hands in his pockets, looking down at the sprawling city skyline that his father's name had built, one clumsy signature at a time, over thirty years.

He didn't hear Binay come back into the room, his footsteps muffled by the thick carpet. 

"They don't believe you can do it," Binay said, his voice coming from behind the leather armchair.

Vikram didn't turn around. "I have been doing it for ten years, Papa, and nobody in that room seemed to notice."

Binay came to stand beside him at the window, his movements slower than they used to be. One of his thin hands briefly found the wooden frame of the glass pane for balance, before he let go of it again, unwilling to be seen needing support.

"That is the wrong complaint, Vikram," the old man said.

"What's the right one?"

"The question was never whether they noticed," Binay said, his eyes scanning the city.

There was a long pause, so long that Vikram finally turned his head to look at him. His father's profile looked sharp and dark against the afternoon light.

"The question is whether you will do it again," Binay said, looking at his son. "Somewhere nobody hands you the ground already prepared. Somewhere you are the kid Reddy thinks you are, because for one honest minute, you actually will be."

Vikram looked back at the glass. The city lights outside had started to flicker on, turning the window into a soft double exposure. 

The boardroom behind him—the long mahogany table, the empty leather chairs, the portrait of his grandfather—was faintly ghosted over the dusty skyline in front of him. 

Somewhere in the overlap of the glass, for just a blink, the reflection looking back at him wasn't a thirty-year-old industrialist in a tailored suit. 

It was thinner. Younger. A first-year student with a hostel corridor phone still warm against one ear, his feet in cheap rubber slippers. 

He blinked, and the image was gone, replaced by the version of himself that had learned, over ten patient years, exactly how much a face can be asked to hold without cracking.

"I did it once already," Vikram said, his hand tightening in his pocket. "When I didn't choose it. When you asked me to."

"Yes."

"This time, I would be choosing it myself."

"Yes," Binay said again. There was something almost like relief in the single word, the sound of a man finally setting down a heavy question he had been carrying longer than his son knew.

Neither of them said the rest of it out loud. 

"Choosing it" this time also meant choosing it without a father in the next room to call if things went wrong. These ten remaining weeks or months were the last stretch of road where Vikram would ever again get to make a decision with Binay Ahuja still alive to see it land.

Vikram didn't answer with words. 

He reached up and straightened the lapels of his jacket. It was the same way he had once straightened a borrowed apron in front of a bathroom mirror before a ragging that turned out to be nothing worth fearing. 

He found that the promise he was making wasn't really to Reddy, who was waiting to be proven wrong in tomorrow's meeting. It wasn't even to the thin man standing beside him, though he owed him more than either of them would ever say plainly.

It was to a nineteen-year-old boy who had once left a Pathology textbook open on a wooden hostel desk, mid-sentence, and never gotten to finish reading it.

*I'll finish something for you,* he thought, his eyes fixed on the reflection of the empty boardroom. *Not that. But something else.*

"Tell them yes, Papa," Vikram said, turning to face his father. "South India. All of it."

Binay Ahuja nodded once. It was the nod of a man who had expected this answer from the beginning, but was still glad to hear it spoken out loud.

They stood together at the window for a while longer, saying nothing else. Below them, the city went on, the headlights of the cars moving along the bypass exactly as they had before either of them had decided anything at all.

